               <head>Fath Ali Shah's letter to Gore Ouseley on submitted petition</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary />
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85100074 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85104368 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2009117611 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008115489" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_4243-item1">
                     <note>
                        <p>Large letter or manshūr with the seal of <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_51026511" ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/n99910124" role="pat">Fatḥ ʿAlī Shāh</persName> (dated 1217/1802) and invocation,
addressesed to  <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_44733962" ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/n93023258" role="rcp">Gore Ouseley</persName>, the English ambassador, acknowledging receipt and deliberation of a petition or ʿarīz̤ah, and additionally giving permission to approach His Majesty in the field. Refers to the issue of a farmān-i mubārak or royal edict to that effect (not enclosed or attached) 
                        </p>
                        <p>Dated: Jum. II 1228/June 1813 </p>
                        <p>Shikastah āmīz; gold ṭughrā style invocation and shikastah āmīz invocation at top </p>
                        <p>Irregularly cropped, stained, old fold lines, and creases</p>
                        <p>IOL stamp: 1 May 1919
</p>
                        <p>Seal impressions on the reverse: ʿAbd al-Vahhāb al-Mūsavī 1225; Muḥammad Shafīʿ; Muḥammad Yūsuf </p>
                        <p>Watermark: 1) Cyrillic inscription; 2) date below 1811; 3) profile figure holding lance with rampant quadruped with scimitar in fenced encloser </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per" otherLangs="eng">Persian &amp; English &amp; Russian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
